            <h3 id="variants">Size</h3>
            <p>Make your copy a comfortable size to read. If you have a ton of copy, you may want to do everything you can to trim it down.</p>

            <p><strong>Headlines</strong> should be no larger than around 40 pixels.</p>

            <p><strong>Body copy</strong> should be around 18-21 pixels for comfortable readability across most devices with a line-height roughly 1.4 times the font size. For smaller legal copy and copyright information, going as small as 13-15 pixels is just fine. Again, the line height should be roughly 1.4 times the font size.</p>

            <h3>Hierarchy</h3>
            <p>Establishing the order of importance allows a user to quickly find what they are looking for. The headers help determine that hierarchy. There are six in order of most important to least important: <code>h1, h2, h3, h4, h5, h6</code> </p>
            <p>There should only be one <code>h1</code> per article or section. For example, on this website, the logo itself is the <code>h1</code> and the section headers are <code>h2</code>.</p>

            <h3>Fallbacks</h3>
            <p>When using web fonts, it is always a good idea to specify fallback fonts. Fallbacks are typefaces that are common system fonts. If a browser doesn’t support a font, it will move on to the next font in the list.</p>

            <p>Here are examples with the preferred fallback order for Open Sans and Courier New respectively:</p>
            <pre>body {
    <span class="commented">/* This is the preferred fallback order for Open Sans */</span>
    font-family: "Open Sans", Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
}

code,
pre {
    <span class="commented">/* This is the preferred fallback order for Monospace fonts */</span>
    font-family: 'courier new', monospace;
}</pre>
            <br>
            <hr>
            <h2>Do's and Don'ts</h2>
            <ul class="dos">
                <li>Use proper content heirarchy. Be very aware of the visual hierarchy of the information and determine the order one would read it in. Divide your text into header text (usually the name of a page, the title of a section, or title of a document) and body copy (anything in normal paragraphs).</li>
                <li>Use line spacing that is around 1.4 times the size of the font.
                    <div class="demo">
                        <span class="toggle"><span class="awesome">This is awesome</span><span class="terrible">These are uncomfortable to read</span>.</span>
                        <div class="goodies line-height">
                            <div class="yep">
                                <p>Cras justo odio, dapibus ac facilisis in, egestas eget quam. Aenean eu leo quam. Pellentesque ornare sem lacinia quam venenatis vestibulum.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="nope">
                                <p>Aenean eu leo quam. Pellentesque ornare sem lacinia quam venenatis vestibulum. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>
                                <p>Integer posuere erat a ante venenatis dapibus posuere velit aliquet. Sum sociis natoque penatibus et magnis dis parturient montes, nascetur ridiculus mus.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>Only use a single space between sentences. Every major style guide agrees.</li>
            </ul>
            <ul class="donts">
                <li>Do not use any decorative typefaces in any correspondence or designs. These fonts should not be used under any circumstance: Papyrus, Comic Sans, Curlz, Brush Script, Impact, Giddyup, Hobo, Wide Latin
                    <div class="demo">
                        <span class="toggle">These fonts are <span class="awesome">awesome</span><span class="terrible">unprofessional</span>.</span>
                        <div class="goodies bad-fonts">
                            <div class="yep">
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Open Sans</li>
                                    <li>Helvetica</li>
                                    <li>Arial</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <div class="nope">
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Papyrus</li>
                                    <li>Comic Sans</li>
                                    <li>Curlz</li>
                                    <li>Brush Script</li>
                                    <li>Impact</li>
                                    <li>Giddyup</li>
                                    <li>Hobo</li>
                                    <li>Wide Latin</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>Do not increase or decrease the letter-spacing.
                    <div class="demo">
                        <span class="toggle"><span class="awesome">This is awesome</span><span class="terrible">These are uncomfortable to read</span>.</span>
                        <div class="goodies letter-spacing">
                            <div class="yep">
                                <p>Cras justo odio, dapibus ac facilisis in, egestas eget quam. Aenean eu leo quam. Pellentesque ornare sem lacinia quam venenatis vestibulum.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="nope">
                                <p>Aenean eu leo quam. Pellentesque ornare sem lacinia quam venenatis vestibulum. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>
                                <p>Integer posuere erat a ante venenatis dapibus posuere velit aliquet. Sum sociis natoque penatibus et magnis dis parturient montes, nascetur ridiculus mus.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>Don't overuse bold, italic, and underline styles. If you use bold too many times, it can lose importance and cause visual clutter.
                    <div class="demo">
                        <span class="toggle">This is <span class="awesome">awesome</span><span class="terrible">cluttered</span>.</span>
                        <div class="goodies overuse">
                            <div class="yep">
                                <p>What was most significant about the lunar voyage was not that man set foot on the Moon but that they set <em>eye</em> on the earth.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="nope">
                                <p>What was most <strong>significant</strong> about the <u>lunar voyage</u> was not that <em>man</em> set foot on the <strong>Moon</strong> but that they set <em>eye</em> on the <u>earth</u>.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>Do not bend or warp the text.</li>
                <li>Do not apply noticeable gradients or bevel effects to the text.</li>
                <li>Do not <span class="spin">rotate</span> the text.</li>
            </ul>
